Figure 2: The two different conditional factorizations used in our experiments, with 1D and 2D local attention on the left and right, respectively. In both, the image is partitioned into non-overlapping query blocks, each associated with a memory block covering a superset of the query block pixels. In every self-attention layer, each position in a query block attends to all positions in the memory block. The pixel marked as q is the last that was generated. All channels of pixels in the memory and query blocks shown in white have masked attention weights and do not contribute to the next representations of positions in the query block. While the effective receptive field size in this figure is the same for both, in 2D attention the memory block balances pixels on the sides and above the query block more evenly.
In our experiments we use two different ways of choosing query blocks and their associated memory block neighborhoods, resulting in two different factorizations of the joint pixel distribution into conditional distributions. Both are illustrated in Figure 2.
1D Local Attention To compute self-attention on raster-scanned linearized images, we partition the length into non-overlapping query blocks Q of length lq, padding with zeroes if necessary. While contiguous in the linearized image, these blocks can be discontiguous in image coordinate space. For each query block we build the memory block M from the same positions as Q and an additional lm positions from pixels that have been generated before, which can result in overlapping memory blocks.
2D Local Attention In local 2D attention models, we generate the image query block by query block in raster-scan order, but for query blocks rectangular in the original image space. Within each block, we generate individual positions again in raster-scan order. As illustrated on the right side of Figure 2, we generate the blocks outlined in grey lines left-to-right and top-to-bottom. This allows us to use 2-dimensional query blocks of a size lq specified by height and width lq = wq · hq, and memory blocks extending the query block to the top, left and right by hm, wm and again wm pixels, respectively.
In both 1D and 2D local attention, we mask attention weights for pixels in the query and memory blocks that have not yet been generated.
As shown in Figure 2, 2D local attention balances horizontal and vertical context much more evenly. We believe this will have an increasingly positive effect on quality with growing image size. 1
4 INFERENCE
Across all of the presented experiments, we sample from the various models with a tempered softmax (Dahl et al., 2017). We adjust the concentration of the distribution we sample from with a temperature  > 0 by which we divide the logits for the channel intensities.
1While our current experiments fail to show an improvement in log-likelihood, upon closer inspection we discovered an error in the implementation of our conditioning for the rightmost pixels that is likely responsible for the low quality of rightmost columns in images generated by the 2D super-resolution models and possibly also affects log-likelihoods significantly. Even with the current implementation, however, we are observing a consistent and significant improvement in visual quality between 1D and 2D super-resolution outputs.
